{"term":"2012","caseName":"Peugh v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/2012/12-62","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - February 26, 2013","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/roberts6/oral_argument_audio/22156","transcript":[{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"We'll hear argument first this morning in Case 12-62, Peugh v. United States.","start":0,"stop":6.07,"duration":6.07},{"text":"Mr. Kinnaird.","start":6.07,"stop":6.97,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":6.97,"stop":11.022,"duration":4.05},{"text":"In sentencing Petitioner Marvin Peugh, the district court applied the 2009 guidelines sentencing range of 70 to 87 months, rather than the 1998 range of 37 to 46 months applicable at the time of his offense.","start":11.022,"stop":31.685,"duration":20.66},{"text":"Retroactive application of harsher guidelines passed after the offense violates the Ex Post Facto Clause if it -- if it creates a significant risk of increased punishment.","start":31.685,"stop":45.112,"duration":13.43},{"text":"Now, the Government here objects that a guidelines amendment does not change the law, but that is incorrect.","start":45.112,"stop":52.016,"duration":6.9},{"text":"The guidelines are legislative rules that define a term of a mandatory statute, mainly subsection (a)(4) of section 18 USC.","start":52.016,"stop":63.84,"duration":11.82}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me.","start":63.84,"stop":64.273,"duration":0.43},{"text":"A mandatory schedule?","start":64.273,"stop":65.275,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Excuse me?","start":65.275,"stop":66.558,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"A mandatory schedule, you say?","start":66.558,"stop":68.81,"duration":2.25}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it's a term of a -- of a mandatory statute, subsection--","start":68.81,"stop":73.612,"duration":4.8}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh, okay.","start":73.612,"stop":74.631,"duration":1.02}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--(a)(4) of -- of 18 USC 3553.","start":74.631,"stop":78.433,"duration":3.8},{"text":"That provision requires the district court to consider the guidelines sentencing range, and I'll quote,","start":78.433,"stop":88.055,"duration":9.62},{"text":"\"established for the applicable category of offense committed by the applicable category of offender. \"","start":88.055,"stop":95.959,"duration":7.9},{"text":"So in 1998, the guide -- that statute, the law mandated that the district court shall consider, as applied to Peugh's offense and offender category a sentencing range of 37 to 46 months.","start":95.959,"stop":113.754,"duration":17.8}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, let's say you prevail and the case is remanded for resentencing.","start":113.754,"stop":117.741,"duration":3.99},{"text":"Is there anything that would prevent the district court from saying, you know, before the promulgation of the new guidelines, I thought the range in the old guidelines was about right for this offense.","start":117.741,"stop":129.449,"duration":11.71},{"text":"But now that I've seen the new guidelines, I think that those really fit best under the factors that I have to consider under the statute in determining the correct sentence, so I'm going to reimpose exactly the same sentence.","start":129.449,"stop":145.624,"duration":16.17},{"text":"Not because it's required by the guidelines, in fact, I'm going to go outside the guidelines.","start":145.624,"stop":149.91,"duration":4.29},{"text":"I just think, with the enlightenment that the new guidelines have provided me, that that's the best sentence.","start":149.91,"stop":157.032,"duration":7.12},{"text":"Would that be -- would there be an ex post facto problem there?","start":157.032,"stop":159.718,"duration":2.69}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it would not, Your Honor.","start":159.718,"stop":161.151,"duration":1.43},{"text":"You would under the statute have to follow all the steps in the Rita/Gall framework, but the district court is always able to consider any developments that it wants.","start":161.151,"stop":171.526,"duration":10.38},{"text":"What we're talking about is the change of law.","start":171.526,"stop":172.942,"duration":1.42},{"text":"And that was the point I was just getting to.","start":172.942,"stop":175.161,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not a change of the law if -- if the law does not require the guidelines to be imposed.","start":175.161,"stop":181.381,"duration":6.22},{"text":"Your -- your case rests upon the proposition you stated at the outset, which is that the Ex Post Facto Law applies -- prohibition applies -- if there is a substantial possibility of -- of a higher sentence -- was that the language you used?","start":181.381,"stop":198.776,"duration":17.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Substantial -- significant risk.","start":198.776,"stop":200.295,"duration":1.52}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Significant risk.","start":200.295,"stop":201.195,"duration":0.9},{"text":"Suppose -- suppose the district judge for the Federal district in which somebody's crime was committed was a -- a bleeding heart judge.","start":201.195,"stop":211.984,"duration":10.79},{"text":"He always gave the lowest sentence possible, and everybody knew that.","start":211.984,"stop":215.738,"duration":3.75},{"text":"And he is replaced.","start":215.738,"stop":218.423,"duration":2.69},{"text":"He retires after the arrest, after the crime, and he is replaced by Maximum John, who everybody knows gives the highest sentence every time.","start":218.423,"stop":231.064,"duration":12.64},{"text":"Ex post -- ex post facto violation?","start":231.064,"stop":234.866,"duration":3.8}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because the Ex Post Facto Clause only applies to laws where here are delegated lawmaking.","start":234.866,"stop":240.084,"duration":5.22},{"text":"And here's where the change in the law was, Your Honor.","start":240.084,"stop":242.77,"duration":2.69},{"text":"As I mentioned, in 1998, the law required the district court to consider a sentencing range of 37 to 46 months.","start":242.77,"stop":252.392,"duration":9.62},{"text":"With the guidelines amendment, the law changed.","start":252.392,"stop":254.428,"duration":2.04},{"text":"The law now required the district court for that category of offender and offense to consider as the--","start":254.428,"stop":262.266,"duration":7.84}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that what your definition of legal consequence is?","start":262.266,"stop":266.135,"duration":3.87}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, legal consequence refers to punishment.","start":266.135,"stop":268.503,"duration":2.37},{"text":"That's something -- that's something different.","start":268.503,"stop":270.103,"duration":1.6},{"text":"So the fact--","start":270.103,"stop":271.472,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So you're taking -- you're disagreeing with the proposition of our older cases that to -- for there to be an ex post facto violation, you have to have a legal consequence.","start":271.472,"stop":281.561,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, not at all, Your Honor.","start":281.561,"stop":282.947,"duration":1.39},{"text":"The legal consequence is the -- is the ultimate sentence imposed.","start":282.947,"stop":286.382,"duration":3.44},{"text":"And in Morales and Lynce, the Court said--","start":286.382,"stop":289.251,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there's a -- there's the disconnect for me.","start":289.251,"stop":292.719,"duration":3.47},{"text":"Yes, I do accept that the district courts have to consider the guidelines, but how do you tie that to the requirement that the punishment has to be tied to the guidelines?","start":292.719,"stop":303.658,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, the Court said in Morales and in Lynce that -- and then when it was reconciled in two different formulations of the standard -- and in Lynce, the Court said it's the same test whether you increase the penalty or whether you determine that there's a sufficient risk of increasing the penalty.","start":303.658,"stop":319.084,"duration":15.43},{"text":"Because that--","start":319.084,"stop":320.036,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Your real formula is significantly increased the risk of perform -- of prolonging the defendant's incarceration.","start":320.036,"stop":327.94,"duration":7.9},{"text":"That's the standard you would like us--","start":327.94,"stop":329.825,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's the standard of Garner and Morales, yes, Your Honor.","start":329.825,"stop":332.444,"duration":2.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--And is -- is the heart of your argument that there really isn't much difference at all in what district judges are doing now that the guidelines are discretionary than what they did when they were mandatory, that is, most of them will start with and stop with the guidelines.","start":332.444,"stop":352.841,"duration":20.4},{"text":"I think that's--","start":352.841,"stop":354.574,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":354.574,"stop":356.392,"duration":1.82},{"text":"That -- that is certainly one element of it.","start":356.392,"stop":358.494,"duration":2.1},{"text":"But the -- the fact -- it's not exactly the same, but the fact is that even under the advisory guidelines, the change in law creates a significant risk.","start":358.494,"stop":367.683,"duration":9.19},{"text":"And when you're evaluating significant risk, I think you have to start from the premise that the ex post facto violation prohibits an increase in punishment of any quantum, even of 1 day.","start":367.683,"stop":381.008,"duration":13.32}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- your -- your brief spent some time on statistics, how often this happens; but I take it you're not saying that our inquiry is a statistical one.","start":381.008,"stop":395.018,"duration":14.01},{"text":"You're simply saying that the statistics bear out that as an objective legal matter, the framework that you are explaining to us is and must be followed?","start":395.018,"stop":405.725,"duration":10.71}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, Your Honor.","start":405.725,"stop":407.442,"duration":1.72},{"text":"The -- and that's -- the inquiry in Garner -- in Garner, the Court said you can demonstrate significant risk either by showing that the risk is inherent in the rule, or as applied to your sentence, and marshalling the evidence of the practical operation of the rule.","start":407.442,"stop":424.218,"duration":16.78},{"text":"So statistical evidence is -- is evidence of the fact of significant risk by the operation of that framework.","start":424.218,"stop":431.557,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the statutes allowing relatives and friends of the victim to testify?","start":431.557,"stop":439.127,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Let's assume a crime committed before -- a horrible crime committed before that statute is enacted, does it violate the ex post facto law to give effect to that statute?","start":439.127,"stop":450.435,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":450.435,"stop":451.887,"duration":1.45},{"text":"I think there's a series of cases saying those kind of changes in trial procedure would not be within the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":451.887,"stop":457.875,"duration":5.99}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Why?","start":457.875,"stop":458.225,"duration":0.35},{"text":"Don't -- don't you think it creates a significant risk--","start":458.225,"stop":460.391,"duration":2.17}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, you have to--","start":460.391,"stop":461.327,"duration":0.94}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--if the defendant will get a higher sentence?","start":461.327,"stop":462.793,"duration":1.47},{"text":"Don't you think that's the whole object of the law, in fact?","start":462.793,"stop":466.295,"duration":3.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, but -- you have to show -- I think you have -- this is a core sentencing law.","start":466.295,"stop":472.198,"duration":5.9},{"text":"It changes the law of punishment, which is different from procedure.","start":472.198,"stop":475.15,"duration":2.95},{"text":"And in Miller, the Court said that when there's a change in the -- in the actual sentencing standard, the number of years, that's substantive, not procedural.","start":475.15,"stop":483.756,"duration":8.61}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What if you have a law that sentencing judges must consider these factors, and one of the factors is whether the defendant has strong family ties that will be, you know, jeopardized or whatever, if he's incarcerated.","start":483.756,"stop":498.766,"duration":15.01},{"text":"You don't want to take him away from his family, because that will penalize other people.","start":498.766,"stop":502.154,"duration":3.39},{"text":"And then Congress thinks that's not a good idea and they take that away.","start":502.154,"stop":505.789,"duration":3.63},{"text":"Is that an ex post facto violation?","start":505.789,"stop":508.391,"duration":2.6},{"text":"It increases the factors of -- or the risk that the defendant will get a higher sentence before he could take advantage of the fact that he had, you know, a particular family situation.","start":508.391,"stop":521.781,"duration":13.39},{"text":"Later, he could not.","start":521.781,"stop":522.817,"duration":1.04},{"text":"That's a change in what the sentencing court must consider and is to his prejudice.","start":522.817,"stop":528.035,"duration":5.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if it is simply a change in the mix of factors, even the mandatory factors, it wouldn't necessarily create a significant risk.","start":528.035,"stop":535.891,"duration":7.86},{"text":"But the guidelines--","start":535.891,"stop":536.991,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, under -- under our modification of the guidelines approach, isn't that just a list of factors that the Court should consider, or must consider?","start":536.991,"stop":545.664,"duration":8.67}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, I think the guidelines are distinctive, because they are the actual benchmark, and they must -- and the starting point for any sentencing.","start":545.664,"stop":554.785,"duration":9.12},{"text":"It is critical that what range you start your sentencing analysis, it's going to affect the analysis whether you're starting at a range of 20 to 30 months or 120--","start":554.785,"stop":565.125,"duration":10.34}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that -- is that what -- who says that they're the benchmark that you start with?","start":565.125,"stop":569.16,"duration":4.03},{"text":"Where is that writ?","start":569.16,"stop":571.062,"duration":1.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's in Gall.","start":571.062,"stop":572.231,"duration":1.17},{"text":"So that's in -- a construction of what's implied in the sentencing format.","start":572.231,"stop":575.933,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"A court -- a court must begin with that.","start":575.933,"stop":578.218,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":578.218,"stop":578.735,"duration":0.52},{"text":"Yeah, that's the -- and the court not only must begin with it, must be cognizant of it throughout the process.","start":578.735,"stop":584.705,"duration":5.97},{"text":"And any--","start":584.705,"stop":586.455,"duration":1.75}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So what if the -- what if the law said the court must begin with a comparison of what the average sentence is across the country, okay?","start":586.455,"stop":598.179,"duration":11.72},{"text":"And the data collection over time becomes more sophisticated and they can give you a more accurate number for what the average sentence is.","start":598.179,"stop":607.737,"duration":9.56},{"text":"And it turns out it's higher than what their informal survey was before.","start":607.737,"stop":612.439,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Is that an ex post facto violation?","start":612.439,"stop":614.308,"duration":1.87}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think necessarily so, but this is a -- a requirement to actually consider a range.","start":614.308,"stop":619.628,"duration":5.32}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No, no.","start":619.628,"stop":620.145,"duration":0.52},{"text":"It'd be the same -- it'd be the same thing.","start":620.145,"stop":621.712,"duration":1.57},{"text":"One of the things that the Sentencing Commission considers is, of course, what the average sentences were around the country.","start":621.712,"stop":628.568,"duration":6.86},{"text":"And let's say that the law says that's something you have to consider, and the technology or the range of -- of judges that they can survey becomes more sophisticated, the number goes up.","start":628.568,"stop":638.339,"duration":9.77}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it may be if you had the exact same Rita and Gall framework--","start":638.339,"stop":642.041,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":642.041,"stop":642.541,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--and that -- that framework is that that range actually is the benchmark and the -- and the starting point.","start":642.541,"stop":648.362,"duration":5.82},{"text":"The district court must justify any deviation from that range -- and this is language from Gall -- with","start":648.362,"stop":655.301,"duration":6.94},{"text":"\"sufficiently compelling justifications to support the degree of the variance. \"","start":655.301,"stop":659.503,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"And so the answer--","start":659.503,"stop":660.62,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"And it is then reviewed on appeal--","start":660.62,"stop":661.372,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--And so the answer to my question is?","start":661.372,"stop":663.039,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--It would be -- I think it would be likely if it were -- if it were within the same framework, if it's the mandatory benchmark with appellate review for substantive reasonableness, and a presumption--","start":663.039,"stop":674.862,"duration":11.82}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm sorry.","start":674.862,"stop":675.462,"duration":0.6},{"text":"Go ahead.","start":675.462,"stop":675.881,"duration":0.42}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--and a presumption of -- of reasonableness on appeal would attach to that standard.","start":675.881,"stop":681.618,"duration":5.74}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So just getting more accurate information violates the Ex Post Facto Clause in the framework that you've set forth?","start":681.618,"stop":687.772,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I think if it's -- if you could -- if it's an actual -- well, I don't know -- the distinction I was trying to draw is that if you actually -- if the statute has effectively delegated the specification of a specific range, as opposed to just a data factor that might change over time.","start":687.772,"stop":705.151,"duration":17.38},{"text":"And that's the key change in law here.","start":705.151,"stop":706.101,"duration":0.95},{"text":"As I mentioned, 1998, had to consider 36 to 47 months.","start":706.101,"stop":712.155,"duration":6.05},{"text":"With the guidelines amendment, the law changed.","start":712.155,"stop":714.673,"duration":2.52},{"text":"He now must consider for that offense and offender category a range of 70 to 87 months, and -- and -- as the mandatory benchmark.","start":714.673,"stop":724.195,"duration":9.52},{"text":"That's a change in the law.","start":724.195,"stop":725.445,"duration":1.25},{"text":"And then you go to the test of significant risk.","start":725.445,"stop":728.314,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What if the -- what if the statistics showed that nationwide only, let's say, 25 percent of defendants were being sentenced within the guideline range; would that change your argument?","start":728.314,"stop":740.389,"duration":12.08}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it makes the -- well, we have an argument that's specific to our sentencing.","start":740.389,"stop":744.443,"duration":4.05},{"text":"But if the -- if in a particular case, a defendant were making an empirical analysis, that may diminish the chance of significant risk, but with a caveat, because it's not just sentences within the guidelines range, it's the fact that the district court, even if it sentences out of the guidelines range, the ultimate amount that it sentences to is going to be partially determined by that mandatory benchmark.","start":744.443,"stop":768.241,"duration":23.8},{"text":"And that -- that's an important point.","start":768.241,"stop":770.26,"duration":2.02},{"text":"And as I said, the significant risk is a risk of any increase in the quantum of punishment.","start":770.26,"stop":776.497,"duration":6.24},{"text":"So it's really, is there a significant risk that had he been -- had the old guidelines been in place as the benchmark, that he would have gotten a -- a sentence of less than 60 -- 70 months.","start":776.497,"stop":788.305,"duration":11.81},{"text":"And--","start":788.305,"stop":788.688,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think there's a fair chance that as time goes by--","start":788.688,"stop":791.038,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it's clear--","start":791.038,"stop":791.421,"duration":0.38}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--we're going to see fewer and fewer sentences within the guidelines.","start":791.421,"stop":795.258,"duration":3.84},{"text":"As judges who began their careers during the guidelines, the mandatory guidelines era, leave the bench, new judges come in who never had to deal with the mandatory guidelines, I think we're going to see fewer and fewer guidelines sentences.","start":795.258,"stop":809.434,"duration":14.18},{"text":"And -- and the percentages in some districts are -- are really quite striking.","start":809.434,"stop":812.719,"duration":3.29},{"text":"I'm told that in the Southern District -- or the Eastern District of New York now, only 30 percent of the defendants receive within-guidelines sentences.","start":812.719,"stop":820.623,"duration":7.9},{"text":"So--","start":820.623,"stop":821.159,"duration":0.54}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You're assuming that's changed over time.","start":821.159,"stop":822.875,"duration":1.72}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, when I was on the court of appeals we thought it was our responsibility to ensure that the district courts were complying with the Sentencing Reform Act.","start":822.875,"stop":835.817,"duration":12.94},{"text":"That might not have been true across the river, but--","start":835.817,"stop":838.202,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"It wasn't.","start":838.202,"stop":841.387,"duration":3.18},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":841.387,"stop":843.156,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Let's say this case comes back in 20 years and the statistics show that only a -- a distinct minority of defendants are being sentenced within the guidelines; would the case come out differently?","start":843.156,"stop":855.646,"duration":12.49}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Perhaps, but again this is an as-applied challenge, so we look to current data.","start":855.646,"stop":861.2,"duration":5.55},{"text":"There has been a very slight gradual decline, but there's still 80 percent of the sentences are either within the guidelines or they're below the guidelines range pursuant to a guidelines sanction departure motion from the government.","start":861.2,"stop":875.044,"duration":13.84},{"text":"So it's an -- even the Sentencing Commission attributes that relationship to the fact that it's the initial starting point in the 2012 Booker report.","start":875.044,"stop":885.916,"duration":10.87},{"text":"So I think it has a profound effect.","start":885.916,"stop":887.535,"duration":1.62},{"text":"Now, if the Court wanted to rule more narrowly in this case on significant risk, it could.","start":887.535,"stop":892.438,"duration":4.9},{"text":"And it could adopt a rule that when the new and the old guidelines ranges do not overlap at all, so that any sentence that would be in the new guidelines range would have required an upward variance, and here a 50 percent upward variance, those are as rare as hen's teeth in the -- in the district courts -- that at least shows at a minimum a significant risk, absent any indication that the judge, as the question was posed, wasn't going to apply them at all.","start":892.438,"stop":924.477,"duration":32.04},{"text":"Here, the judge specifically and expressly deferred to the 2009 guidelines.","start":924.477,"stop":929.845,"duration":5.37},{"text":"So it's clear that the significant risk was increased by this change in the law.","start":929.845,"stop":935.765,"duration":5.92}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Your -- your case depends, it seems to me, upon the proposition that significant risk is only applicable at the sentencing stage.","start":935.765,"stop":943.871,"duration":8.11},{"text":"And I'm not sure that that's true.","start":943.871,"stop":945.806,"duration":1.94},{"text":"I mean, what -- why -- why would that be so?","start":945.806,"stop":949.508,"duration":3.7},{"text":"What if -- what if you have a new law that permits evidence to come in, in a criminal trial that previously was not allowed to come in, let's say the testimony of a wife or whatever.","start":949.508,"stop":959.631,"duration":10.12},{"text":"I think the law is pretty well established that that change in procedure does not violate the ex post facto law.","start":959.631,"stop":968.22,"duration":8.59},{"text":"And your response to that is: Well, that's not sentencing; it's trial.","start":968.22,"stop":972.123,"duration":3.9},{"text":"So what?","start":972.123,"stop":972.857,"duration":0.73},{"text":"I mean, if -- certainly making a conviction more likely is -- is even worse than making a higher sentence more likely.","start":972.857,"stop":984.015,"duration":11.16}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I think my response would be, Your Honor, that's not -- that particular change would not be in the third category of Calder, the increase in punishment.","start":984.015,"stop":991.835,"duration":7.82},{"text":"That would be in the fourth category, in the changes of the evidence where you don't even look to significant risk.","start":991.835,"stop":997.739,"duration":5.9},{"text":"But I think the -- the change in punishment, at a minimum, it's the sentencing law of this kind--","start":997.739,"stop":1003.81,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"And would it be ex post facto in -- in the hypothetical Justice Scalia gave?","start":1003.81,"stop":1007.897,"duration":4.09}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--No, I don't think so, because I think -- well, it may, depending on the circumstances, be within the fourth category, but not under the third.","start":1007.897,"stop":1016.3,"duration":8.4},{"text":"I think in the third--","start":1016.3,"stop":1017.569,"duration":1.27}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Can you tell me the narrow rule that you would propose--","start":1017.569,"stop":1020.104,"duration":2.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1020.104,"stop":1020.554,"duration":0.45}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--getting back to Justice Scalia--","start":1020.554,"stop":1024.656,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"The narrow rule--","start":1024.656,"stop":1024.94,"duration":0.28}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--which is procedures change risks.","start":1024.94,"stop":1028.294,"duration":3.35},{"text":"Having a victim testify at sentences -- at a sentence is likely, if you examined it statistically, to increase -- increase the sentence.","start":1028.294,"stop":1041.102,"duration":12.81},{"text":"So assume that's the set of hypotheticals.","start":1041.102,"stop":1044.054,"duration":2.95},{"text":"You change it, now victims can.","start":1044.054,"stop":1046.772,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Why is that not or is it an ex post facto change?","start":1046.772,"stop":1050.374,"duration":3.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I don't think so, because the Court has generally excluded procedural changes even if you could show--","start":1050.374,"stop":1055.777,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So why is this not procedural?","start":1055.777,"stop":1057.094,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Because the--","start":1057.094,"stop":1058.479,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Give me the rule where I can draw a line between those changes that are permissible and those that are not, not the general statement you're making, because both increase the risk of a higher sentence.","start":1058.479,"stop":1071.221,"duration":12.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":1071.221,"stop":1071.687,"duration":0.47}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"So it can't be that.","start":1071.687,"stop":1072.437,"duration":0.75}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No.","start":1072.437,"stop":1072.756,"duration":0.32},{"text":"What Miller -- what Miller said -- in Miller v. Florida the argument was made that a change in the sentencing range, the presumptive range, was a change in procedure, and the Court said, no, that's substantive.","start":1072.756,"stop":1083.029,"duration":10.27},{"text":"This is the substantive benchmark that is applied.","start":1083.029,"stop":1086.064,"duration":3.04},{"text":"It's a substance standard.","start":1086.064,"stop":1087.164,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"--But that was in the -- that Florida case was the mandatory, almost mandatory guideline, and I think our starting point is -- your starting point, too -- is that when the guidelines were mandatory it was ex post facto because our decision in the Florida case said it was.","start":1087.164,"stop":1108.846,"duration":21.68},{"text":"Is this sufficiently different now that the guidelines are advisory rather than mandatory?","start":1108.846,"stop":1116.583,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor.","start":1116.583,"stop":1117.352,"duration":0.77},{"text":"I think it would still be a substantive standard regardless of whether it's binding or -- or whether it's advisory.","start":1117.352,"stop":1124.589,"duration":7.24},{"text":"It's still a substantive standard.","start":1124.589,"stop":1126.958,"duration":2.37},{"text":"So if it's a change in the substantive sentencing law, you go to significant risk analysis.","start":1126.958,"stop":1130.843,"duration":3.88},{"text":"And there you either look to the inherent risk, and I think there is an inherent risk in this framework that there's going to be some increase of some quantum of punishment beyond what they would have done if they'd applied the older guidelines as the mandatory benchmark.","start":1130.843,"stop":1146.871,"duration":16.03}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"But saying that the sentencer has to consider testimony from the victim or from relatives of the deceased, that -- that change in sentencing law is okay?","start":1146.871,"stop":1160.429,"duration":13.56}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Under the fact that it's considered a procedural law, not substantive.","start":1160.429,"stop":1165.416,"duration":4.99}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"It pertains to sentencing.","start":1165.416,"stop":1167.201,"duration":1.79},{"text":"It -- it says what the sentencing authority, the judge or the jury, must consider.","start":1167.201,"stop":1173.272,"duration":6.07}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well--","start":1173.272,"stop":1174.455,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"This is evidence brought before the sentencer.","start":1174.455,"stop":1176.806,"duration":2.35}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, yes.","start":1176.806,"stop":1177.573,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't see any difference between that and saying that the -- the guidelines have to be considered by the sentencer.","start":1177.573,"stop":1182.977,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I may have misheard your -- your hypothetical.","start":1182.977,"stop":1186.496,"duration":3.52},{"text":"In that case, it may very well be a sentencing -- a sentencing law, it may pass that threshold, and then you go to significant risk.","start":1186.496,"stop":1194.035,"duration":7.54},{"text":"I would say significant risk is more difficult to determine than in this particular case, where you have the actual starting point, an actual number, which has--","start":1194.035,"stop":1203.874,"duration":9.84}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You're answering me differently now?","start":1203.874,"stop":1205.41,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm sorry?","start":1205.41,"stop":1206.01,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"You're answering me differently?","start":1206.01,"stop":1207.876,"duration":1.87},{"text":"I posed exactly the question that Justice Scalia--","start":1207.876,"stop":1210.195,"duration":2.32}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I -- I may have misheard, Your Honor.","start":1210.195,"stop":1211.314,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"--I said the sentencing -- the assumptions I made were the sentencing law changes, victims must testify, judges must consider what they say, and after 5 years it's proven that when victims speak the sentences are higher.","start":1211.314,"stop":1227.989,"duration":16.67},{"text":"Is that a substantive or a procedural law?","start":1227.989,"stop":1230.358,"duration":2.37}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think Miller did draw a distinction.","start":1230.358,"stop":1235.595,"duration":5.24},{"text":"There are procedures that are involved in sentencing, and I'm not sure if the Court's procedure-substance cases have drawn that distinction.","start":1235.595,"stop":1244.368,"duration":8.77},{"text":"If it--","start":1244.368,"stop":1245.418,"duration":1.05}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm asking you to draw it.","start":1245.418,"stop":1246.737,"duration":1.32},{"text":"So tell me what's the rule?","start":1246.737,"stop":1247.487,"duration":0.75},{"text":"Do you want something as broad that says even that kind of change can be an ex post facto?","start":1247.487,"stop":1253.891,"duration":6.4},{"text":"And if you don't, articulate how I draw the line?","start":1253.891,"stop":1257.842,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think -- I think the Court could draw the line simply on substantive standards that are applied.","start":1257.842,"stop":1262.162,"duration":4.32},{"text":"But if the Court were to go the other direction, significant risk--","start":1262.162,"stop":1266.548,"duration":4.39}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What does that mean to you, the number of years in jail?","start":1266.548,"stop":1268.233,"duration":1.68}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1268.233,"stop":1269.016,"duration":0.78}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Is that as limited as you want it to be?","start":1269.016,"stop":1270.602,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it could be.","start":1270.602,"stop":1272.818,"duration":2.22},{"text":"I mean, or at least -- you know, if it's a mandatory sentencing factor, something like that, as opposed to--","start":1272.818,"stop":1278.006,"duration":5.19}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we know that's Miller.","start":1278.006,"stop":1278.739,"duration":0.73}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":1278.739,"stop":1279.374,"duration":0.63}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"This is not Miller.","start":1279.374,"stop":1280.491,"duration":1.12}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but even the -- there are sentencing factors that are mandatory other than the guidelines range.","start":1280.491,"stop":1286.378,"duration":5.89}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I would have thought you would have gone back to Calder v. Bull.","start":1286.378,"stop":1289.564,"duration":3.19},{"text":"And Calder v. Bull, which this Court refers to all the time in these kinds of cases, has four categories and the only one that fits this case is a law that changes the punishment--","start":1289.564,"stop":1302.387,"duration":12.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1302.387,"stop":1303.256,"duration":0.87}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--and inflicts a greater punishment than the law annexed to the crime when committed.","start":1303.256,"stop":1308.827,"duration":5.57},{"text":"So whatever these other hypotheticals are, they do not involve -- they are not laws that change the punishment.","start":1308.827,"stop":1317.081,"duration":8.25},{"text":"But yours is a law that changes the punishment.","start":1317.081,"stop":1320.616,"duration":3.54}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"It is a law that changes--","start":1320.616,"stop":1322.635,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Does it “ affix a higher punishment ”, in the words of Calder v. Bull?","start":1322.635,"stop":1325.92,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it--","start":1325.92,"stop":1326.47,"duration":0.55}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I don't think that's a question at all.","start":1326.47,"stop":1328.139,"duration":1.67},{"text":"The answer to that is quite easy.","start":1328.139,"stop":1330.507,"duration":2.37},{"text":"It does not affix a higher punishment, does it?","start":1330.507,"stop":1333.109,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--But -- but the Court in Garner, in Lynce, have equated that with increased risk of significant punishment.","start":1333.109,"stop":1339.429,"duration":6.32},{"text":"And that -- the importance of Garner is that it recognizes that that the Ex Post Facto Clause--","start":1339.429,"stop":1344.833,"duration":5.4}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":1344.833,"stop":1345.383,"duration":0.55},{"text":"Then rely on Garner, but not on Calder v. Bull.","start":1345.383,"stop":1347.116,"duration":1.73}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1347.116,"stop":1348.135,"duration":1.02},{"text":"I think -- but Garner is applying that--","start":1348.135,"stop":1350.404,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I wouldn't concede that.","start":1350.404,"stop":1351.787,"duration":1.38}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"That doesn't help--","start":1351.787,"stop":1352.387,"duration":0.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Okay.","start":1352.387,"stop":1352.737,"duration":0.35},{"text":"So what Garner -- what Garner does say is that you look to the significant risk.","start":1352.737,"stop":1358.272,"duration":5.53},{"text":"And it's important for ex post facto -- ex post facto jurisprudence, because the exercise of discretion can't displace ex post facto protections.","start":1358.272,"stop":1369.263,"duration":10.99},{"text":"You have to look at the effect on the actual punishment.","start":1369.263,"stop":1372.365,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you remind me -- it's in the briefs -- if a sentence is appealed, what is the review authority of the appellate court?","start":1372.365,"stop":1383.606,"duration":11.24},{"text":"It must begin with the guidelines as the framework?","start":1383.606,"stop":1388.66,"duration":5.05}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"The review authority is to review for both procedural and substantive reasonableness.","start":1388.66,"stop":1394.73,"duration":6.07},{"text":"So procedural I think has been interpreted to look at whether there was a correct calculation, whether they -- they did not treat it as mandatory, that they considered it as the benchmark and the--","start":1394.73,"stop":1406.038,"duration":11.31}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But isn't the important point, Mr. Kinnaird, that there's a presumption of correctness that attaches to guidelines sentences on appeal--","start":1406.038,"stop":1413.025,"duration":6.99}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":1413.025,"stop":1413.425,"duration":0.4}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"--that does not attach to non-guidelines sentences?","start":1413.425,"stop":1415.394,"duration":1.97}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1415.394,"stop":1415.677,"duration":0.28},{"text":"I was getting to that, Your Honor.","start":1415.677,"stop":1417.694,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I mean, this is, one would think, great legal consequence.","start":1417.694,"stop":1421.798,"duration":4.1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"It is.","start":1421.798,"stop":1422.648,"duration":0.85},{"text":"And the second step is substantive reasonableness review and the Court has held that an appellate presumption of reasonableness may attach.","start":1422.648,"stop":1431.569,"duration":8.92},{"text":"So that attaches only to this guideline range.","start":1431.569,"stop":1434.355,"duration":2.79},{"text":"And that makes the risk of reversal higher if you -- if you go outside the guidelines.","start":1434.355,"stop":1439.259,"duration":4.9}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you know what the statistics are as to the number of below-guidelines sentences each year that are reversed by the courts of appeals on the ground that they are not reasonable?","start":1439.259,"stop":1450.833,"duration":11.57}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think that they are fairly low -- I don't know the precise statistics -- I believe they're low for defendant appeals.","start":1450.833,"stop":1461.173,"duration":10.34},{"text":"But partly you're worried about here is -- is the government going to appeal.","start":1461.173,"stop":1464.708,"duration":3.54},{"text":"They don't appeal very often, but they have a high rate of--","start":1464.708,"stop":1466.243,"duration":1.53}]},{"speakerName":"Samuel A. Alito, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1466.243,"stop":1466.777,"duration":0.53},{"text":"I mean, I think it's in the single digits.","start":1466.777,"stop":1467.31,"duration":0.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--I believe the -- yes, it may be -- I don't know.","start":1467.31,"stop":1470.278,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It's not a great number, but they prevail when they do.","start":1470.278,"stop":1474.265,"duration":3.99},{"text":"And it -- and it does have some effect, which I think the Court--","start":1474.265,"stop":1477.05,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Counsel, who prevails?","start":1477.05,"stop":1477.417,"duration":0.37},{"text":"The government or the--","start":1477.417,"stop":1478.417,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"--The government tends to prevail when it brings.","start":1478.417,"stop":1479.836,"duration":1.42},{"text":"But, you know, that's a potential deterrent effect.","start":1479.836,"stop":1483.721,"duration":3.88},{"text":"But even the fact of substantive reasonableness review, you have to have reasons, you have to be able to justify your deviations.","start":1483.721,"stop":1491.025,"duration":7.3}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Have you had -- are you aware of any circuit court case in recent time where a circuit has reversed the lower range than the guideline, basically because the deviation from the guideline was unreasonable?","start":1491.025,"stop":1506.737,"duration":15.71}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"I'm not sure.","start":1508.82,"stop":1506.737,"duration":-2.08},{"text":"I haven't reviewed all those cases, Your Honor.","start":1506.737,"stop":1509.22,"duration":2.48},{"text":"So the -- returning to the question of this particular sentencing, I think if the Court were to rule on a narrower ground based on non-overlapping ranges, which is not going to be particularly common, here there's unquestionably a significant risk.","start":1509.22,"stop":1528.15,"duration":18.93},{"text":"You have a defendant who prior to this course of conduct had lived an exemplary life.","start":1528.15,"stop":1532.971,"duration":4.82},{"text":"His threshold -- his -- the loss in his case barely crawled into the 2.5 million to 5 million.","start":1532.971,"stop":1540.225,"duration":7.25},{"text":"It was about 40,000 over 2.5 million.","start":1540.225,"stop":1543.66,"duration":3.44},{"text":"And the district court sentenced at the bottom of the guidelines range, agreeing with the policy of increasing sentences with the amount of loss.","start":1543.66,"stop":1553.015,"duration":9.36},{"text":"That same policy was present, but not the same level of increase, in the 1998 guidelines.","start":1553.015,"stop":1559.621,"duration":6.61},{"text":"So I think there's clearly, as applied to his sentence, the significant risk he would not have gotten 70 months, which would have been an upward variance of 50 -- of 50 percent from the old guidelines range.","start":1559.621,"stop":1572.696,"duration":13.07},{"text":"But I think if the Court does wish to consider the broader ruling, I think it's also true that it is inherent in this system, in the Rita and Gall framework, which provide for a mandatory benchmark, which provide for the substantive reasonableness review, that you're going to have some significant risk of some increased quantum of punishment as a result of this change in law.","start":1572.696,"stop":1597.627,"duration":24.93},{"text":"I'd like to reserve the rest of my time for rebuttal.","start":1597.627,"stop":1599.579,"duration":1.95}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Thank you, counsel.","start":1599.579,"stop":1600.865,"duration":1.29},{"text":"Mr. Feigin.","start":1600.865,"stop":1611.137,"duration":10.27}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice, and may it please the Court:","start":1611.137,"stop":1614.506,"duration":3.37},{"text":"This Court made clear in Miller v. Florida that an Ex Post Facto Law has to change, quote,","start":1614.506,"stop":1619.91,"duration":5.4},{"text":"\"the legal consequences of a prior act. \"","start":1619.91,"stop":1622.279,"duration":2.37},{"text":"A guidelines amendment doesn't do that.","start":1622.279,"stop":1624.445,"duration":2.17},{"text":"A district court has the same authority and the same--","start":1624.445,"stop":1627.933,"duration":3.49}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Why are you fighting this proposition?","start":1627.933,"stop":1631.384,"duration":3.45},{"text":"Because the starting point doesn't matter.","start":1631.384,"stop":1634.252,"duration":2.87},{"text":"Why didn't you stick to your old position that judges should start from the old one and simply consider the new one?","start":1634.252,"stop":1641.823,"duration":7.57},{"text":"Why this whole Supreme Court case?","start":1641.823,"stop":1644.958,"duration":3.13}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, we -- we opposed certiorari largely on that ground.","start":1644.958,"stop":1649.196,"duration":4.24},{"text":"We don't think the guidelines impose a constraint on a district court's exercise of sentencing discretion.","start":1649.196,"stop":1654.916,"duration":5.72},{"text":"That is, if a judge decides that a guidelines range that the commission has suggested at some other time suggests a more appropriate sentence or if the judge believes that some sentence that's unrelated to any guidelines range is the most appropriate sentence, the judge has discretion to impose that sentence.","start":1654.916,"stop":1671.443,"duration":16.53}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"Practically speaking, do you believe it makes no difference?","start":1671.443,"stop":1674.311,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I freely believe that the guidelines are very influential to many district judges and district judges often agree with the guidelines.","start":1674.311,"stop":1684.369,"duration":10.06},{"text":"They often impose sentences within the guidelines range or close to the guidelines range.","start":1684.369,"stop":1688.987,"duration":4.62}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"This is a change -- your position is -- is a change, at least in the position that the Government took in -- in the Seventh Circuit case that started all this.","start":1688.987,"stop":1700.362,"duration":11.38},{"text":"The Government confessed error.","start":1700.362,"stop":1702.397,"duration":2.03},{"text":"The Government said the district judge should have used the guidelines that were in effect at the time the offense was committed, and the Government came to the Seventh Circuit and confessed error.","start":1702.397,"stop":1718.756,"duration":16.36},{"text":"So there was not even an argument until the Seventh Circuit and Judge Posner wrote the opinion that included all the hypotheticals that -- that were aired earlier about the victim impact statement and all of those are in that opinion.","start":1718.756,"stop":1735.202,"duration":16.45},{"text":"So it was only after -- after the Seventh Circuit opinion that the Government changed its position.","start":1735.202,"stop":1741.606,"duration":6.4}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the Government changed its position in response to this Court's decisions in Gall, Kimbrough and Irizarry, because before those decisions came out, there was an argument that the guidelines still imposed some substantive legal constraint on a district court's sentencing discretion.","start":1741.606,"stop":1756.531,"duration":14.92},{"text":"After Gall, Kimbrough and Irizarry, after Nelson and Spears, that argument no longer exists.","start":1756.531,"stop":1762.769,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Rita makes clear that district courts cannot presume a guidelines range to be reasonable.","start":1762.769,"stop":1767.654,"duration":4.88},{"text":"Irizarry makes clear that a defendant is constitutionally on notice that he can get sentenced anywhere within the statutory range, and Gall makes clear that courts of appeals should apply the same deferential standard of review to every sentence regardless whether it falls within the guidelines range, just outside the guidelines range, or far outside the guidelines range.","start":1767.654,"stop":1787.051,"duration":19.4}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"The guidelines range gets a presumption of reasonableness at the appellate level.","start":1787.051,"stop":1794.055,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"That's right, Your Honor, and I think Rita actually supports our position, not Petitioner's.","start":1794.055,"stop":1798.942,"duration":4.89},{"text":"The Court made clear in Rita that the presumption of reasonableness on appeal that this -- that courts of appeals can choose to apply, but need not, has no legal effect.","start":1798.942,"stop":1806.881,"duration":7.94},{"text":"Rather, it reflects the commonsense proposition that when the commission recommends a particular sentencing range as to a particular class of defendants and the district court, in its discretion, actually imposes the sentence within that range, that the sentence is likely to be reasonable.","start":1806.881,"stop":1823.741,"duration":16.86},{"text":"The entire premise behind the presumption of reasonableness that was adopted in Rita is that district courts are in fact exercising their discretion when they impose sentences, and that's the same premise on which we'd ask you to decide this case.","start":1823.741,"stop":1835.116,"duration":11.38}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the reason that miscalculating a guideline is considered a procedural error?","start":1835.116,"stop":1843.387,"duration":8.27}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, it's very clear from 3553(a)(4) that Congress wants district courts to start with the right mix of information, which includes the most up-to-date recommendation of the Sentencing Commission.","start":1843.387,"stop":1856.212,"duration":12.83}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"That begs the question.","start":1856.212,"stop":1857.231,"duration":1.02},{"text":"Obviously, if we hold it's a procedural error to miscalculate the guidelines, using the guidelines has some significant importance in the process.","start":1857.231,"stop":1871.657,"duration":14.43}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"It has importance, Your Honor, and as I've said before, they can be very influential to judges, but the reason why it's an error to miscalculate the guidelines is not because the guidelines impose any substantive constraint on the district court's discretion.","start":1871.657,"stop":1884.381,"duration":12.72},{"text":"After reversal for miscalculating the guidelines, the judge is free to impose the same sentence anyway, and there's no constraint on the judge's discretion that arises from the guidelines frame.","start":1884.381,"stop":1893.654,"duration":9.27}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But what that suggests is that the guidelines serve as an anchor and are supposed to serve as an anchor, and that the reason why the miscalculation is error is because you've picked the wrong anchor and that's going to affect or -- or has a significant likelihood of affecting your ultimate decision.","start":1893.654,"stop":1911.866,"duration":18.21},{"text":"And isn't that really what we've suggested is the way the guidelines ought to work, and the way you think the guidelines ought to work, that it serves as an anchor for sentencing decisions.","start":1911.866,"stop":1922.221,"duration":10.36},{"text":"Yes, you can vary, you can deviate, but it's your anchor.","start":1922.221,"stop":1925.923,"duration":3.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, there are two things you could mean when you use the word “ anchor ”.","start":1925.923,"stop":1929.041,"duration":3.12},{"text":"One, you could mean that there's some sort of legal anchor, and we think that the Court's decisions that I've just described, in particular, the Court's repeated insistence that district courts cannot presume a guidelines range to be reasonable, means the district courts cannot treat them as a legal anchor.","start":1929.041,"stop":1943.718,"duration":14.68},{"text":"Second, you might be suggesting that they serve as some sort of psychological anchor.","start":1943.718,"stop":1948.805,"duration":5.09},{"text":"That's not a concern of the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":1948.805,"stop":1951.241,"duration":2.44},{"text":"The Ex Post Facto Clause doesn't guarantee defendants a right to a judge who has a particular sentencing philosophy.","start":1951.241,"stop":1956.895,"duration":5.65}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I think I'm saying more than it's all in your head.","start":1956.895,"stop":1959.097,"duration":2.2},{"text":"I think I'm saying you start in a particular place, you have to get the particular place right.","start":1959.097,"stop":1965.084,"duration":5.99},{"text":"The appellate court looks at the particular place that you've started and if you -- if you've ended up there, has to grant a presumption of reasonableness.","start":1965.084,"stop":1973.857,"duration":8.77},{"text":"But the rules are all geared towards saying, yes, you can deviate, but you have to understand that there's -- that -- deviation requires some kind of thought process and some kind of reason.","start":1973.857,"stop":1988.08,"duration":14.22},{"text":"Otherwise, this is where you should be.","start":1988.08,"stop":1990.116,"duration":2.04}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, the Court made clear in Pepper two terms ago that the district court's overarching legal duty is to impose a sentence sufficient but not greater than necessary to meet the statutory purposes of sentencing in section 3553(a)(2).","start":1990.116,"stop":2003.174,"duration":13.06},{"text":"The guidelines are one of several factors that inform the district court's exercise of discretion.","start":2003.174,"stop":2008.011,"duration":4.84},{"text":"If a district court treats the guidelines as some sort of legal constraint this Court's decisions say it can't be treated as, that would be statutory error.","start":2008.011,"stop":2016.784,"duration":8.77}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it isn't, but that I think is an undecided question at best.","start":2016.784,"stop":2020.469,"duration":3.68},{"text":"If you won the case on that ground, I would say that what the guidelines and the Sentencing Commission are best at, gathering information from across the country and saying a typical person who commits this crime in a typical way should be sentenced to the typical range that applies, let's say 18 to 24 months.","start":2020.469,"stop":2042.834,"duration":22.37},{"text":"That would be down the drain.","start":2042.834,"stop":2044.703,"duration":1.87},{"text":"And I think that Rita, in fact, and the other cases have at the very most left open and maybe decided against you the question of when a court of appeals gets the sentence from a judge who does not apply the guideline because he doesn't like the policy judgment.","start":2044.703,"stop":2062.129,"duration":17.43},{"text":"That's a different matter from when he applies it and when he thinks he shouldn't apply it because the person in front of him doesn't meet the policy conditions.","start":2062.129,"stop":2074.888,"duration":12.76},{"text":"Those are different.","start":2074.888,"stop":2076.288,"duration":1.4},{"text":"The commission has the expertise in the first, the judge in the second.","start":2076.288,"stop":2080.626,"duration":4.34},{"text":"And so there is at least a question as to whether the court of appeals should give more leeway to the guidelines in the first and more leeway to the judge in the second.","start":2080.626,"stop":2092.517,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Now, I think Rita is consistent with that, and I think every opinion we have written is consistent with that.","start":2092.517,"stop":2098.088,"duration":5.57},{"text":"And I'd hate to see that suddenly decided and changed in a way I think is inappropriate in this case.","start":2098.088,"stop":2103.741,"duration":5.65},{"text":"So have you all thought that through?","start":2103.741,"stop":2106.124,"duration":2.38},{"text":"And is the position of the Government now that we think the guidelines, even if it's a policy matter that they have gathered evidence on, are entitled to nothing if they run across a district judge who happens to think, though he was an outlier, that the outliers were right as a matter of policy, which of course will always be true.","start":2106.124,"stop":2125.405,"duration":19.28},{"text":"Every judge who is an outlier thinks the outliers are right.","start":2125.405,"stop":2128.79,"duration":3.38},{"text":"Otherwise why would he do it?","start":2128.79,"stop":2130.04,"duration":1.25},{"text":"You see?","start":2130.04,"stop":2131.392,"duration":1.35},{"text":"Now, I didn't know that issue was in this case and that changes the case dramatically for me.","start":2131.392,"stop":2138.313,"duration":6.92},{"text":"And I thought we could decide this just on the ground that this is a law that changes punishment.","start":2138.313,"stop":2145.484,"duration":7.17},{"text":"It's a law.","start":2145.484,"stop":2146.651,"duration":1.17},{"text":"It's a regulation.","start":2146.651,"stop":2147.701,"duration":1.05},{"text":"And Justice Scalia I thought was completely right.","start":2147.701,"stop":2150.972,"duration":3.27},{"text":"The question is whether it inflicts greater punishment.","start":2150.972,"stop":2154.674,"duration":3.7},{"text":"And there is a test on that and the controlling inquiry is whether retroactive application of a change in a law that affects punishment created a sufficient risk of increasing the measure of punishment attached.","start":2154.674,"stop":2168.065,"duration":13.39},{"text":"All right?","start":2168.065,"stop":2169.35,"duration":1.28},{"text":"And that's -- that's what I thought the framework of law was in this case.","start":2169.35,"stop":2173.886,"duration":4.54},{"text":"Now, this is sort of tough for you on oral argument because I'm just, perhaps, bringing it all up to get it all out there and see what you think.","start":2173.886,"stop":2183.693,"duration":9.81}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me start at the end there, Justice Breyer.","start":2183.693,"stop":2185.36,"duration":1.67}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I disagree with all that, by the way.","start":2185.36,"stop":2186.978,"duration":1.62},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":2186.978,"stop":2190.613,"duration":3.63}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, Your Honor, Justice Breyer, beginning with what you said at the end there, I think it would be inappropriate to untether the significant risk test from the requirement that there be an ex post facto law.","start":2190.613,"stop":2203.338,"duration":12.73},{"text":"That is, there has to be a significant legal risk, a risk that is traceable to some sort of change in the decisionmaker's authority with respect to sentencing, and we don't have that here.","start":2203.338,"stop":2213.713,"duration":10.38},{"text":"A district court has the same authority and the same obligation to impose an appropriate sentence the day after the guidelines are amended as the judge had the day before the guidelines are amended.","start":2213.713,"stop":2224.569,"duration":10.86},{"text":"And any judge who forgets that is going to be committing statutory error, and the sentence could be reversed on appeal for violating the Booker remedy.","start":2224.569,"stop":2231.591,"duration":7.02},{"text":"And that's--","start":2231.591,"stop":2232.775,"duration":1.18}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But when it comes to the court of appeals, it's different.","start":2232.775,"stop":2236.743,"duration":3.97},{"text":"The court of appeals begins with a framework of whether or not it's within the guidelines.","start":2236.743,"stop":2241.095,"duration":4.35},{"text":"That's how it begins to measure the exercise of discretion.","start":2241.095,"stop":2245.083,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, as I've explained, the reason why courts -- the only way in which courts of appeals can apply a different standard of review to a sentence, depending on where it falls in the guidelines range, is the presumption of reasonableness the Court recognized in Rita.","start":2245.083,"stop":2259.156,"duration":14.07},{"text":"And I think Rita makes quite clear that that is a practical presumption.","start":2259.156,"stop":2263.71,"duration":4.55},{"text":"That is, it simply acknowledges the commonsense proposition that when a district court exercising its discretion reaches a judgment that accords with the commission's expertise, it's likely that sentence is reasonable.","start":2263.71,"stop":2275.352,"duration":11.64},{"text":"I don't think--","start":2275.352,"stop":2275.968,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"I know there is a lot of dispute now about the child pornography sentences.","start":2275.968,"stop":2281.356,"duration":5.39},{"text":"Let's assume -- and this goes back to Justice Breyer's question -- a judge comes in and says: I know child pornography is criminal, but I don't think what the guidelines are imposing are fair to any defendant.","start":2281.356,"stop":2299.467,"duration":18.11},{"text":"So, 10 days in jail.","start":2299.467,"stop":2304.787,"duration":5.32},{"text":"Why would that be substantively unreasonable?","start":2304.787,"stop":2308.156,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, it would depend on the individual circumstances of the particular case.","start":2308.156,"stop":2312.375,"duration":4.22}]},{"speakerName":"Sonia Sotomayor","textObjs":[{"text":"No, I'm giving you exactly what the judge says.","start":2312.375,"stop":2314.26,"duration":1.89},{"text":"You don't think that the appellate court would say that's substantively unreasonable because it's not giving due deference to the commission's assessment of the seriousness of this crime?","start":2314.26,"stop":2332.039,"duration":17.78}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"I think the court of appeals might say that it's substantively unreasonable because it's a very, very low sentence even in comparison to the statute.","start":2332.039,"stop":2339.044,"duration":7}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume that the statute is one that permits 10 days, right?","start":2339.044,"stop":2342.679,"duration":3.64},{"text":"Sort of an unusual statute, but if the hypothetical is in the real world, the statute provides, you know, 10 days to life, okay?","start":2342.679,"stop":2352.935,"duration":10.26},{"text":"And the judge thinks 10 days is okay.","start":2352.935,"stop":2355.737,"duration":2.8},{"text":"I think that's the hypothetical.","start":2355.737,"stop":2357.856,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"And, Your Honor, in that case, it is possible a court of appeals would decide that that is substantively unreasonable.","start":2357.856,"stop":2366.112,"duration":8.26},{"text":"It's possible a court of appeals might reference the guidelines.","start":2366.112,"stop":2367.178,"duration":1.07},{"text":"But the reason why the court of appeals would find it substantively unreasonable is because as a whole it is substantively unreasonable and not because it varies too far from the guidelines.","start":2367.178,"stop":2377.05,"duration":9.87},{"text":"I also want to emphasize--","start":2377.05,"stop":2378.252,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Do you disagree with -- getting back to what this case is about, the D.C. Circuit, in opposition to the Seventh Circuit said:","start":2378.252,"stop":2388.208,"duration":9.96},{"text":"\"It is enough that using the new guideline created a substantial risk that the defendant's sentence was more severe that it would have been if the guidelines in effect at the time of the crime were used. \"","start":2388.208,"stop":2411.474,"duration":23.27},{"text":"And it said,","start":2411.474,"stop":2412.474,"duration":1},{"text":"\"There is no doubt that this case fits that description. \"","start":2412.474,"stop":2415.877,"duration":3.4},{"text":"\"There was quite a substantial risk that the elevated guidelines would result in a more severe sentence. \"","start":2415.877,"stop":2427,"duration":11.12}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, there are two complaints that Petitioner could be making about his particular sentencing.","start":2427,"stop":2434.006,"duration":7.01},{"text":"One could be that he thinks the judge treated the guidelines too deferentially as a legal matter.","start":2434.006,"stop":2439.826,"duration":5.82},{"text":"And if that's what he believes, his remedy is a claim of statutory error under Booker.","start":2439.826,"stop":2443.945,"duration":4.12},{"text":"He's never made that claim.","start":2443.945,"stop":2445.564,"duration":1.62},{"text":"The other claim--","start":2445.564,"stop":2446.447,"duration":0.88}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"He's saying that -- the question is which guidelines in this case?","start":2446.447,"stop":2451.718,"duration":5.27},{"text":"And he's saying it's the guidelines in effect at the time he committed the crime.","start":2451.718,"stop":2458.054,"duration":6.34},{"text":"We are not dealing with other -- I mean, it's quite a simple choice.","start":2458.054,"stop":2462.423,"duration":4.37},{"text":"Is it -- does the court start with the guidelines in effect at the time the crime was committed or does it start with the guidelines in effect at the time of sentencing?","start":2462.423,"stop":2475.499,"duration":13.08}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--And whichever set of guidelines the district court started with, it had discretion and in fact the obligation to impose the appropriate sentence under 3553(a).","start":2475.499,"stop":2485.039,"duration":9.54}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, we know that this district judge, he didn't want to get into any philosophical things about what was better or what was worse.","start":2485.039,"stop":2492.193,"duration":7.15},{"text":"He said, I want to follow the guidelines.","start":2492.193,"stop":2493.811,"duration":1.62},{"text":"So the question for him was only which guideline.","start":2493.811,"stop":2497.68,"duration":3.87},{"text":"He got his answer from the Seventh Circuit.","start":2497.68,"stop":2500.131,"duration":2.45},{"text":"They said the guidelines at the time of sentencing.","start":2500.131,"stop":2503.816,"duration":3.68},{"text":"A judge in the D.C. District Court will get the other answer, the guidelines in effect at the time the crime was committed.","start":2503.816,"stop":2515.208,"duration":11.39}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, Petitioner argued in this case that the former guidelines range suggested a more appropriate sentence than the 2009 guidelines range.","start":2515.208,"stop":2523.647,"duration":8.44},{"text":"The district court considered that argument and it rejected it.","start":2523.647,"stop":2526.532,"duration":2.89},{"text":"And defendants are always free to raise that argument.","start":2526.532,"stop":2528.634,"duration":2.1},{"text":"If I could go back to Justice Sotomayor's child pornography hypothetical--","start":2528.634,"stop":2532.003,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"It's not -- it's not a question of whether the judge thought that the one guideline was better than the other.","start":2532.003,"stop":2539.573,"duration":7.57},{"text":"He specifically said he wasn't interested in that question.","start":2539.573,"stop":2542.977,"duration":3.4},{"text":"The question was which guideline does he follow.","start":2542.977,"stop":2546.179,"duration":3.2},{"text":"What does he start with?","start":2546.179,"stop":2548.145,"duration":1.97},{"text":"And you recognize that you do start with the guidelines.","start":2548.145,"stop":2553.583,"duration":5.44}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I agree with Justice Ginsburg's follow-up question.","start":2553.583,"stop":2556.551,"duration":2.97},{"text":"It seems to me you avoid the question.","start":2556.551,"stop":2558.07,"duration":1.52},{"text":"You said, oh, well, the judge looked at all this and selected the sentence he did.","start":2558.07,"stop":2562.105,"duration":4.03},{"text":"But he did so because he referred to the later guidelines and I think you have to recognize that.","start":2562.105,"stop":2567.676,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"I think you are saying that it doesn't matter because they are advisory--","start":2567.676,"stop":2571.045,"duration":3.37}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I'd like to finish.","start":2571.045,"stop":2572.413,"duration":1.37},{"text":"Unless I am wrong under the record.","start":2572.413,"stop":2574.63,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Well, Your Honor, on the record, I think if you look at the full sentencing transcript, which is in the Joint Appendix, you will see that one of the questions the judge had to answer was which set of guidelines were provided -- were the set of guidelines that he had to calculate under 3553(A)(4)(a)(2).","start":2574.63,"stop":2590.958,"duration":16.33},{"text":"And then there was a separate section in which he considered the argument that the 2009 guidelines were too harsh.","start":2590.958,"stop":2596.695,"duration":5.74},{"text":"If you look at the sentencing memorandum that Petitioner filed in this case, it argued that the increase in loss amounts in the fraud guidelines was too harsh, that judges often impose sentences that are the guidelines, and the district court should do so here.","start":2596.695,"stop":2610.103,"duration":13.41},{"text":"The district court considered that argument and rejected that.","start":2610.103,"stop":2613.055,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But the district court was following orders.","start":2613.055,"stop":2615.324,"duration":2.27},{"text":"He was following the Seventh Circuit.","start":2615.324,"stop":2617.109,"duration":1.78},{"text":"The Seventh Circuit had said: You start with the higher guidelines.","start":2617.109,"stop":2621.393,"duration":4.28}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Justice Ginsburg, it's -- as the Court considers these as two separate questions, one is which is the set of guidelines I'm required to calculate under Section 3553(a), and second, having calculated those guidelines, what sentence should I impose, with the guidelines as one of the factors that the Court consider.","start":2621.393,"stop":2640.141,"duration":18.75}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Feigin, you're sounding awfully like according deference to the guidelines counts as reversible error.","start":2640.141,"stop":2646.295,"duration":6.15}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"No, Your Honor, that's not what I'm trying to say.","start":2646.295,"stop":2648.997,"duration":2.7},{"text":"I'm saying treating the guidelines as some sort of legal constraint on the district court's sentencing discretion is reversible error.","start":2648.997,"stop":2655.401,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Now, if the district court chooses in its own discretion to give weight to the guidelines, that's within the realm of choice that 3553(a) provides.","start":2655.401,"stop":2664.339,"duration":8.94},{"text":"There are many circumstances--","start":2664.339,"stop":2665.406,"duration":1.07}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"--It is reversible error, is it not, simply to blindly apply the guidelines without considering the factors in 3553?","start":2665.406,"stop":2673.112,"duration":7.71},{"text":"That's reversible, isn't it?","start":2673.112,"stop":2674.212,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's correct, Your Honor.","start":2674.212,"stop":2675.295,"duration":1.08},{"text":"And, Justice Kagan--","start":2675.295,"stop":2677.064,"duration":1.77}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"But surely, you do not want judges living in a world where they think that they cannot give deference to the guidelines; isn't that right?","start":2677.064,"stop":2685.92,"duration":8.86},{"text":"You want them to give appropriate deference to the guidelines; isn't that correct?","start":2685.92,"stop":2690.122,"duration":4.2}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, we want them to find the guidelines persuasive and influential.","start":2690.122,"stop":2693.959,"duration":3.84},{"text":"We recognize that under this Court's decisions, they cannot treat the guidelines as a legal constraint on their sentencing discretion.","start":2693.959,"stop":2700.18,"duration":6.22},{"text":"If a judge follows the guidelines, that's because the judge is exercising its discretion to decide that a guidelines range sentence is appropriate in that particular case.","start":2700.18,"stop":2709.218,"duration":9.04},{"text":"Now, there are many instances in which judges choose not to do that.","start":2709.218,"stop":2711.57,"duration":2.35},{"text":"So, for example, Justice Sotomayor brought up child pornography.","start":2711.57,"stop":2714.772,"duration":3.2},{"text":"In fiscal year 2012, a defendant for a non-production child pornography offense, that is, receipt or possession of child pornography, was substantially more likely to get a nongovernment-sponsored below-range sentence than to get a within-range sentence; 48.4 percent nongovernment-sponsored below-range, 32.7 percent within range.","start":2714.772,"stop":2734.853,"duration":20.08},{"text":"If we want to talk about fraud for a minute, which is what the Petitioner in this case was charged with, if you look at page 67 of the commission's post-Booker report, and I'd encourage the Court to read that report in full, because it makes very clear the variations in sentencing practices among -- depending on the crime, depending on the particular circuit, depending on the particular district, and even depending on the particular judge.","start":2734.853,"stop":2758.551,"duration":23.7}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"Was Judge Randolph wrong when he said, quoting the sentencing commission, that within-guidelines range, even after Booker, is the standard?","start":2758.551,"stop":2772.776,"duration":14.22},{"text":"Indeed, the actual impact of Booker on sentencing has been minor, and for that minor, he cites the sentencing commission.","start":2772.776,"stop":2783.683,"duration":10.91}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"So, Your Honor, I think the post-Booker report refutes that in the respect I just suggested.","start":2783.683,"stop":2788.237,"duration":4.55},{"text":"It says that there are actually very different sentencing practices, depending on the particular crime, depending on the particular judge.","start":2788.237,"stop":2793.807,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Ruth Bader Ginsburg","textObjs":[{"text":"But this statement comes from Final Report on the Impact of the United States v. Booker on Federal Sentencing.","start":2793.807,"stop":2801.145,"duration":7.34}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, the commission says many things in its report.","start":2801.145,"stop":2805.882,"duration":4.74},{"text":"One of the things it says is that in the aggregate, guidelines do -- actual sentences do tend to track the guidelines.","start":2805.882,"stop":2812.869,"duration":6.99},{"text":"But if you look beyond that one aggregate statistic and you start to look at the variations in sentencing practices in courts across the nation that vary not only by judge but by guideline, you see that the system is actually operating the way you'd expect to--","start":2812.869,"stop":2826.112,"duration":13.24}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"I see -- I see now where you're going.","start":2826.112,"stop":2827.978,"duration":1.87},{"text":"What I think you're saying is whatever the sentence is -- I am the judge, I read the guidelines.","start":2827.978,"stop":2834.016,"duration":6.04},{"text":"Now, I may think that I am more likely to get reversed if I substitute a different view than the commission had on a matter of policy.","start":2834.016,"stop":2842.872,"duration":8.86},{"text":"That's all true.","start":2842.872,"stop":2844.074,"duration":1.2},{"text":"But still, I don't have to do it.","start":2844.074,"stop":2847.276,"duration":3.2},{"text":"No matter what it is, I can not use the guidelines.","start":2847.276,"stop":2852.161,"duration":4.89},{"text":"And if I get reversed on other grounds or the sentence is not reasonable, da, da, da, da, da.","start":2852.161,"stop":2856.548,"duration":4.39},{"text":"But there's no legal binding nature there.","start":2856.548,"stop":2859.517,"duration":2.97},{"text":"That's your point, I think.","start":2859.517,"stop":2861.134,"duration":1.62}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--That's exactly my point, Your Honor.","start":2861.134,"stop":2862.619,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"All right.","start":2862.619,"stop":2862.801,"duration":0.18},{"text":"If that's exactly your point--","start":2862.801,"stop":2863.636,"duration":0.84}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"I'd like to add two -- two observations to that, first of which is, as an empirical matter, it is extremely unlikely for a sentence to get reversed on substantive reasonableness grounds.","start":2863.636,"stop":2875.676,"duration":12.04},{"text":"The commission's post-Booker report -- and I'm talking about the one that they just issued a few weeks ago that's cited in the reply brief -- states that substantive unreasonableness reversals are very rare.","start":2875.676,"stop":2884.382,"duration":8.71},{"text":"Petitioner, on page 30 of his brief, cites a database that contains 38 such reversals post Gall.","start":2884.382,"stop":2891.471,"duration":7.09}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen G. Breyer","textObjs":[{"text":"--But now I can narrow what the question I think is.","start":2891.471,"stop":2893.705,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"And the second point I'd like to make, Your Honor, with respect to that is that I don't think this Court should assume that district courts are actually going to change what sentences they impose and not impose the sentence they believe is sufficient, but no greater than necessary to meet the purposes of sentencing just because they--","start":2893.705,"stop":2907.73,"duration":14.03}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, but that -- that gets back to -- to your argument.","start":2907.73,"stop":2910.932,"duration":3.2},{"text":"You're -- I sense that you want me to leave the bench saying the guidelines just don't make any difference.","start":2910.932,"stop":2917.17,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Suppose -- suppose the district judge said, you know, if it were just up to me, I would give this lower sentence, but the guidelines are an important institutional part of our system.","start":2917.17,"stop":2928.828,"duration":11.66},{"text":"Uniformity in sentencing is -- is desirable.","start":2928.828,"stop":2932.632,"duration":3.8},{"text":"For us to take into account the experience of other -- of other courts and what the sentencing commission does is very important.","start":2932.632,"stop":2939.802,"duration":7.17},{"text":"Therefore, my discretion is guided by these guidelines.","start":2939.802,"stop":2943.088,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Your Honor, I absolutely--","start":2943.088,"stop":2945.122,"duration":2.03}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"You don't want me -- you don't want me to say that.","start":2945.122,"stop":2946.372,"duration":1.25}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--I absolutely do not want you to leave the bench with the impression that the guidelines are unimportant.","start":2946.372,"stop":2950.343,"duration":3.97},{"text":"I want you to leave the bench with the impression that the guidelines don't impose any legal constraint on a judge's exercise of discretion.","start":2950.343,"stop":2957.08,"duration":6.74},{"text":"Different judges -- not only does it vary by guideline, but--","start":2957.08,"stop":2960.282,"duration":3.2}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Feigin, take this example.","start":2960.282,"stop":2962.067,"duration":1.78},{"text":"Let's suppose that there's a crime and the punishment for crime is 5 years to life, all right?","start":2962.067,"stop":2967.269,"duration":5.2},{"text":"Now, Congress passes a statute and it says, no, we think this crime now is much more important than we used to, now it's 25 years to life, right?","start":2967.269,"stop":2975.975,"duration":8.71},{"text":"A -- a person commits the offense prior to that change.","start":2975.975,"stop":2982.379,"duration":6.4},{"text":"Absolutely obvious case, right, that you have to apply the -- the 5 years to life, right?","start":2982.379,"stop":2988.634,"duration":6.26},{"text":"Obvious, correct?","start":2988.634,"stop":2990.418,"duration":1.78}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--Yes.","start":2990.418,"stop":2990.918,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"Okay.","start":2990.918,"stop":2991.503,"duration":0.59},{"text":"Now, the Sentencing Commission does what the Sentencing Commission always does when there is a legislative change like this.","start":2991.503,"stop":2998.84,"duration":7.34},{"text":"It says, well, we have this guidelines that assumes 5 years to life.","start":2998.84,"stop":3001.673,"duration":2.83},{"text":"We have to change our guidelines because now it's 25 years to life.","start":3001.673,"stop":3005.494,"duration":3.82},{"text":"And it passes a guideline amendment which completely conforms to the legislative amendment.","start":3005.494,"stop":3011.314,"duration":5.82},{"text":"But you're saying, no, the 25-year-to-life guideline is the appropriate one to implement, even though the 5-year statute is the appropriate one to implement -- is the appropriate one to give effect to.","start":3011.314,"stop":3025.991,"duration":14.68},{"text":"Can that possibly be right?","start":3025.991,"stop":3028.258,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I think I'm saying something slightly different.","start":3028.258,"stop":3030.175,"duration":1.92},{"text":"I think under 3553(a), the Court would calculate the current guidelines.","start":3030.175,"stop":3035.363,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Now, the defendant would have a very good argument in that case that the current guidelines range would simply not be appropriate for him, and I think a district court would do well to listen to that argument in that particular case if it thought that the sentences that the new guidelines range was suggesting were out of whack with the statute at the time the offense was committed.","start":3035.363,"stop":3055.593,"duration":20.23}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Feigin, I'm under the impression -- more than the impression I know -- that the Sentencing Commission can make a revision of the guidelines retroactive.","start":3055.593,"stop":3066.449,"duration":10.86},{"text":"Can it only do that for revisions that lower the -- the suggested penalty or can it do that for revisions that increase it as well?","start":3066.449,"stop":3078.542,"duration":12.09}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"I believe it's only for revisions that lower--","start":3078.542,"stop":3080.558,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Antonin Scalia","textObjs":[{"text":"Only for lower, okay.","start":3080.558,"stop":3082.244,"duration":1.69},{"text":"Because if it could increase it, then it would be violating, according to your friend, the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":3082.244,"stop":3088.731,"duration":6.49}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--And, Your Honor, getting back to how the advisory guidelines are working in practice for a minute, which again is I don't think what this -- what the focus should be.","start":3088.731,"stop":3098.004,"duration":9.27},{"text":"The focus should be on whether there's actually been a change in the law that either increases or decreases a sentencer's discretion.","start":3098.004,"stop":3105.626,"duration":7.62},{"text":"If you imagine two States, for example, each of which had exactly the same advisory guidelines system that the Federal Government has, and in one of them judges are, you know, tend to find the guidelines very persuasive, they sentence within the guidelines 70 percent of the time.","start":3105.626,"stop":3119.5,"duration":13.87},{"text":"In the other one, judges exercising their discretion don't find the guidelines very persuasive and they sentence within the guidelines 10 percent of the time.","start":3119.5,"stop":3126.356,"duration":6.86},{"text":"I don't think it makes sense that under the exact same legal regime an amendment to the guidelines in one State would be an Ex Post Facto Law and an amendment to the guidelines in the other State wouldn't be an Ex Post Facto Law.","start":3126.356,"stop":3138.062,"duration":11.71}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"But your statement to me was -- and to us earlier -- was that there is no legal constraint on the exercise of discretion.","start":3138.062,"stop":3147.269,"duration":9.21},{"text":"I agree, the judge -- everybody knows the judge can go lower.","start":3147.269,"stop":3149.502,"duration":2.23},{"text":"But that overlooks the fact that discretion is defined by legal standards.","start":3149.502,"stop":3156.625,"duration":7.12},{"text":"That's how we begin to think about discretion.","start":3156.625,"stop":3158.993,"duration":2.37},{"text":"That's how appellate courts weigh discretion.","start":3158.993,"stop":3161.21,"duration":2.22},{"text":"And, again, you want to give the guidelines no effect in determining how that discretion is shaped, guided and exercised.","start":3161.21,"stop":3169.099,"duration":7.89}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, they are a factor.","start":3169.099,"stop":3170.968,"duration":1.87},{"text":"They're a factor under 3553(a).","start":3170.968,"stop":3173.085,"duration":2.12},{"text":"They're a factor that the district court has to consider.","start":3173.085,"stop":3175.753,"duration":2.67},{"text":"But they don't themselves in any way, shape, or form constrain the district court's exercise of discretion.","start":3175.753,"stop":3182.174,"duration":6.42},{"text":"A district court can decide that -- not to impose a guidelines sentence.","start":3182.174,"stop":3186.811,"duration":4.64}]},{"speakerName":"Anthony M. Kennedy","textObjs":[{"text":"Would you accept the fact that they define the discretion even though they don't constrain it?","start":3186.811,"stop":3190.862,"duration":4.05}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"Your Honor, I wouldn't say they define the discretion either.","start":3190.862,"stop":3193.714,"duration":2.85},{"text":"I think they are a recommendation and information that informs the exercise of discretion--","start":3193.714,"stop":3198.368,"duration":4.65}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"What if -- I'm sorry.","start":3198.368,"stop":3199.784,"duration":1.42},{"text":"Are you finished?","start":3199.784,"stop":3200.501,"duration":0.72}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--I'm happy to be, Your Honor.","start":3200.501,"stop":3202.403,"duration":1.9},{"text":"[Laughter]","start":3202.403,"stop":3205.438,"duration":3.04}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"A good advocate.","start":3205.438,"stop":3207.64,"duration":2.2},{"text":"Let's say you had a statute -- not a guideline, a statute -- that said a sentence for a particular offense will be 5 years, but the judge can lower it to 4 years if he thinks it would be a manifest injustice to sentence to 5 years.","start":3207.64,"stop":3223.483,"duration":15.84},{"text":"That provision is later repealed.","start":3223.483,"stop":3226.201,"duration":2.72},{"text":"Now it just says that the sentence should be 5 years.","start":3226.201,"stop":3228.47,"duration":2.27},{"text":"Does that violate the Ex Post Facto Clause?","start":3228.47,"stop":3230.737,"duration":2.27}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it might well violate the Ex Post Facto Clause, Your Honor, because in that case you have something we don't have here, which is that the decisionmaker has less discretion than--","start":3230.737,"stop":3238.676,"duration":7.94}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"No matter how narrow -- no matter how narrow the original grant of discretion is?","start":3238.676,"stop":3242.98,"duration":4.3},{"text":"In other words, only in the case of manifest injustice, or however dramatic you want to limit the available discretion.","start":3242.98,"stop":3250.717,"duration":7.74}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--The reason -- the reason I said “ might well ” is I think at that point the Court would have to look at the significance of the increase or decrease in the sentencer's authority, and decide whether that was a significant enough increase or decrease to trigger the--","start":3250.717,"stop":3262.858,"duration":12.14}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"How would -- how would a Court--","start":3262.858,"stop":3263.358,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":3263.358,"stop":3263.541,"duration":0.18}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--Right.","start":3263.541,"stop":3263.841,"duration":0.3},{"text":"How would a Court go about answering that question?","start":3263.841,"stop":3266.226,"duration":2.39}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that's where the significant risk test comes in.","start":3266.226,"stop":3268.343,"duration":2.12},{"text":"And under the significant risk test, you can either see whether it facially has that effect -- we know that's not true of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines because the Court's made clear they don't impose any legal constraints, or you could see whether it has that effect as applied under Garner.","start":3268.343,"stop":3281.586,"duration":13.24},{"text":"We know that--","start":3281.586,"stop":3282.086,"duration":0.5}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"So it's a statistical evaluation of the kind we were talking about.","start":3282.086,"stop":3286.388,"duration":4.3},{"text":"You look and you say, well, it's only once in a blue moon that the judge invokes the manifest injustice provision, so it's not increasing the risk.","start":3286.388,"stop":3295.16,"duration":8.77},{"text":"On the other hand, well, every four out of five judges do and therefore it is an increase.","start":3295.16,"stop":3300.964,"duration":5.8},{"text":"Is that how you--","start":3300.964,"stop":3301.964,"duration":1}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--I think it's fundamental -- the decision in Garner doesn't precisely describe exactly how the significant risk inquiry works.","start":3301.964,"stop":3309.086,"duration":7.12},{"text":"I think it is fundamentally a legal inquiry, because the bottom-line question the Court's always trying to answer is whether there has been an ex post facto law.","start":3309.086,"stop":3318.609,"duration":9.52},{"text":"And I think, to the extent it's okay to look at empirical data -- and I don't think the Court in Garner expressly says that that's the kind of data it was contemplating -- it would be to inform how the legal framework actually operates in practice.","start":3318.609,"stop":3331.417,"duration":12.81},{"text":"And if the Court found it necessary to look at that here, in -- the post-Booker report makes clear that sentencing practices vary over the districts, over the circuits, and with respect to particular guidelines.","start":3331.417,"stop":3344.141,"duration":12.72},{"text":"So Justice Alito brought up the example of the Eastern District of New York.","start":3344.141,"stop":3346.926,"duration":2.78},{"text":"We don't have to look any further than the Northern District of Illinois, where Petitioner was sentenced here, where the latest 2012 statistics that came out on Friday show that a defendant actually has a slightly higher probability, very slightly higher probability, of getting a non-government-sponsored below-range sentence than of getting a sentence within the guidelines range.","start":3346.926,"stop":3365.221,"duration":18.3},{"text":"I think all these variances show two things.","start":3365.221,"stop":3367.756,"duration":2.53},{"text":"One, they show that the system is working exactly as you'd expect an advisory system to work.","start":3367.756,"stop":3372.375,"duration":4.62},{"text":"And two, I think they show that some sort of narrow focus on empirical data, which is what you are left with once you divorce the ex post facto inquiry from a change in law, is inherently unworkable.","start":3372.375,"stop":3382.516,"duration":10.14},{"text":"You have to--","start":3382.516,"stop":3383.133,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"Elena Kagan","textObjs":[{"text":"I think more goes into it than empirics.","start":3383.133,"stop":3386.968,"duration":3.84},{"text":"But there's this unbelievable chart really in one of the green briefs about -- you know, where there's one line which is what happens to the guidelines and there's this other line which is what happens to the sentence, and they follow each other identically, exactly.","start":3386.968,"stop":3402.161,"duration":15.19},{"text":"You can't get a chart that looks better from this than -- from Mr. Kinnaird's point of view.","start":3402.161,"stop":3406.731,"duration":4.57}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--So let me say two things in response to that, Your Honor.","start":3406.731,"stop":3408.75,"duration":2.02},{"text":"If you look in the post-Booker report, they have charts like that that are broken down by offense--","start":3408.75,"stop":3413.202,"duration":4.45}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"--You can finish your sentence.","start":3413.202,"stop":3415.404,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"Eric J. Feigin","textObjs":[{"text":"--If you look at fraud and you look at child pornography, they deviate when they go in -- when the guidelines' suggestion goes up, the sentences don't go up in accordance with that at the same level of the chart you are looking at.","start":3415.404,"stop":3427.228,"duration":11.82},{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3427.228,"stop":3428.428,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3428.428,"stop":3428.83,"duration":0.4},{"text":"Mr. Kinnaird, you have 3 minutes left.","start":3428.83,"stop":3430.713,"duration":1.88}]},{"speakerName":"Stephen B. Kinnaird","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, Mr. Chief Justice.","start":3430.713,"stop":3432.782,"duration":2.07},{"text":"Five quick points.","start":3432.782,"stop":3435.25,"duration":2.47},{"text":"First, the Government says this must be an overt legal restraint to be within the Ex Post Facto Clause.","start":3435.25,"stop":3441.554,"duration":6.3},{"text":"This Court has repeatedly, in Weaver and other cases, said it's the effect of the change of law, not its form, that matters for ex post facto purposes, the effect on punishment.","start":3441.554,"stop":3451.594,"duration":10.04},{"text":"And what this revision and amendment of the mandatory benchmark did was to alter the legal framework in a way that channelled and redefined the exercise of discretion in the direction of greater punishment.","start":3451.594,"stop":3464.254,"duration":12.66},{"text":"Secondly, what range is the -- is the mandatory benchmark under the statute matters greatly, as Justice Kennedy alluded to, to appellate review for substantive reasonableness.","start":3464.254,"stop":3476.561,"duration":12.31},{"text":"You have -- it's the key factor in determining whether a sentence is reasonable, and it's the standard to which a presumption of reasonableness may attach.","start":3476.561,"stop":3486.433,"duration":9.87},{"text":"Third, as far as the record, there's -- there's no analysis in the record of the 1998 guidelines other than to -- to set them aside.","start":3486.433,"stop":3495.539,"duration":9.11},{"text":"And -- and what you have to have under the Constitution is, he has to actually apply those as the statute required at the time of the offense, as the mandatory benchmark.","start":3495.539,"stop":3505.479,"duration":9.94},{"text":"Instead, he's quite clear, he's applying the '98 guidelines.","start":3505.479,"stop":3509.948,"duration":4.47},{"text":"He's deferring to the -- to the policy judgments there, and to the loss calculations.","start":3509.948,"stop":3516.186,"duration":6.24},{"text":"So it had a clear substantive effect on his risk of greater punishment.","start":3516.186,"stop":3520.138,"duration":3.95},{"text":"The post-Booker report does have those line -- those charts that show that for all offenses and for fraud offenses, when the guidelines' minimum goes up, the average sentences go up, and that's a very compelling point of evidence.","start":3520.138,"stop":3536.766,"duration":16.63},{"text":"And finally, I would point out here that one of the amendments here was actually a response of the commission to a congressional directive in the wake of the Enron scandal and the Sarbanes-Oxley Act, where there was great public and legislative outrage over light fraud sentences, to reconsider the fraud guidelines.","start":3536.766,"stop":3557.113,"duration":20.35},{"text":"And that puts this in the core of the Ex Post Facto Clause, that it violates fundamental notions of retroactivity for a legislature to be able to alter the law of punishment after the offense.","start":3557.113,"stop":3568.237,"duration":11.12},{"text":"Thank you.","start":3568.237,"stop":3568.854,"duration":0.62}]},{"speakerName":"John G. Roberts, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, counsel.","start":3568.854,"stop":3569.971,"duration":1.12},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":3569.971,"stop":3571.023,"duration":1.05}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Roberts Court","arguedOn":"Feb 26, 2013","petitioner":"Marvin Peugh","respondent":"United States","docket":"12-62","citation":"569 US 530 (2013)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/569/530","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit","grantedOn":"Nov 9, 2012","decidedOn":"Jun 10, 2013"}